{{short description|Legislature during the Panchayat regime of Nepal}} {{Politics of Nepal}}
'''Rastriya Panchayat''' was the official [[legislature|legislature (parliament)]] (parliament) during the [[Panchayat (Nepal)| Panchayat regime]] of [[Nepal]] that effectively functioned from 1960 to 1990.<ref> {{cite web| url = http://eap.bl.uk/database/overview_item.a4d?catId=57937;r=27644 | title = Endangered Archives}} </ref> Its head office was at the ''"Gallery Baithak"'' in [[Singha Durbar]], [[Kathmandu]]. In the 1980s, it consisted of more than 120 members among which 105 members were directly elected by the people, while the king was to nominate 20 percent of its members, i.e. 19 members were nominated by the monarch.
The Rastriya Panchayat was dissolved by [[Birendra of Nepal| King Birendra]] after the [[People's Movement I (1990) | People's Movement I in 1990]]<ref> {{cite web| url=http://www.telegraphnepal.com/headline/2014-02-14/nepal:-ca-body-similar-to-last-rastriya-panchayat-claims-dahal.html| title=Nepal: CA body similar to last Rastriya Panchayat, claims Dahal}} </ref> and replaced by a [[bicameral legislature]] with a fully elected [[House of Representatives (Nepal)|House of Representatives]] ({{lang-ne|Pratinidhi Sabha}}).
